 research. This is normally because the abstract was not required at the time of proposal submission, but may be because it included sensitive information such as personal details.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Research in chemical biology underpins much of the pharmaceuticals and biotechnology sectors of the UK economy as well as other sectors such as, for example, agrochemicals, consumer products and the food sector. |In 2009, the International Review (IR) of Chemistry (http://www.epsrc.ac.uk/research/intrevs/2009ChemistryIR/Pages/default.aspx) highlighted this area as a key strength of the UK research landscape. The IR panel also identified Drug Discovery as one of three areas (alongside Energy and Materials for Medicine) where the UK chemistry community in its broadest sense has the potential to make a significant contribution to worldwide societal challenges, but can only do so in partnership with UK industry. |Despite large investment by the Research Councils in chemical biology research (current total spend estimated at around #100 million per annum) evidence suggests that only a small proportion of this portfolio is collaborative with industry and other users. Chemical Biology has been an MRC priority for a number of years, as highlighted through the MRC-EPSRC joint highlight notice. There is a particular need for research at the interface between medicinal chemistry and pharmacology, and structure-based drug design. Building on common interests/priorities in this area, the BBSRC, EPSRC and MRC held a joint workshop in June 2010 to bring together industry and academics working in chemical biology in an effort to promote collaborative working. Following on from the event, it was agreed that there was a real opportunity to strengthen collaborative working between disciplines and research sectors to better position them to respond to the challenges in chemical biology. |</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="htt